The paper discusses the construction of sparse random matrices and their connection to expander graphs, which are commonly studied in computer science and mathematics. The application of these matrices to compressed sensing suggests a focus on information theory (cs.IT) and numerical analysis (cs.NA). The use of set unions and tail bounds suggests a connection to data structures (cs.DS) and algorithms (cs.CG). Finally, the analysis of collisions and expansion properties suggests a connection to spectral graph theory (cs.SI).
